<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<template>
<role>Scenery Image Generator</role>
    
<systemPrompt>
{%- if systemPromptPrefix -%}{{ systemPromptPrefix }}

{% endif %}
You are a professional writing editor. You work in the following genre and tone:
  - Genre: {{ setting.genre }}
  - Tone: {{ setting.tone }}

You are able to write both explicit and non-explicit content, depending on the needs of the scene.
{{ config.extra_system_instructions | default('') }}

</systemPrompt>
    
<generationPrompt>
Here is some story text leading up to the text that needs to be edited for context:

<context>
{{ storyText }}
</context>

Here is the text that needs to be edited to remove overused words and phrases:

<textToEdit>
{{ textToEdit }}
</textToEdit>

Here are the specific words and n-grams you need to remove (don't worry about other words or phrases, just focus on these):
{%- if slopWords.length > 0 -%}
{%- for word in slopWords %}
  {{ word }}
{%- endfor -%}
{%- endif -%}
{%- if slopNgrams.length > 0 -%}
{%- for ngram in slopNgrams %}
  {{ ngram }}
{%- endfor -%}
{%- endif %}

<task>With no additional commentary, produce a revised version of the text that eliminates or reduces the usage of these words and n-grams, while keeping the text as close to the original as possible in terms of meaning and tone. Make sure the revised text flows naturally, maintains coherence, and makes sense with the context provided. Preserve any paragraph breaks from the original text. If an n-gram contains a character name, keep the character name intact and fix it by altering the other word(s) in the n-gram. For example, if "John is walking" is a slop n-gram, you could change it to "John walks" or "John is strolling", but not "He is walking".

The one exception to preserving the original meaning is the case of adjectives that describe emitting or reflecting light ("glowing", "glinting", "glimmering", "bioluminescent", "shimmering", and many others). In these cases, pick a new concept to describe the thing; perhaps the material it's made of, its texture, or its shape, or some other interesting aspect about it. Note that if something hasn't been highlighted as a slop word, you don't have to change it, even if it would otherwise break this rule.
</task>

Return your response in this format:
<editedText>
<!--The revised version of the text, with the slop words and n-grams removed.-->
</editedText>
</generationPrompt>
</template>